Wayward husband
comes to his senses...

1623
01:51:51,545 --> 01:51:53,714
returns to his wife...

1624
01:51:53,755 --> 01:51:56,758
with whom he's established
a long and sustaining love.

1625
01:51:58,093 --> 01:52:01,972
Heartless young woman left alone
in her arctic desolation.

1626
01:52:05,142 --> 01:52:07,144
Music up with a swell.

1627
01:52:10,189 --> 01:52:11,899
Final commercial.

1628
01:52:14,735 --> 01:52:18,197
And here are a few scenes
from next week's show.

1629
01:52:30,334 --> 01:52:32,252
How'd it go?

1630
01:52:48,769 --> 01:52:53,440
Mr. Jensen was unhappy at the idea
of taking Howard Beale off the air.

1631
01:52:54,775 --> 01:52:56,944
Mr. Jensen thinks Howard Beale
is bringing...

1632
01:52:57,027 --> 01:53:00,823
a very important message
to the American people.

1633
01:53:03,116 --> 01:53:06,495
So he wants Howard Beale on the air,
and he wants him kept on.

1634
01:53:08,664 --> 01:53:11,959
Mr. Jensen feels we're too catastrophic
in our thinking.

1635
01:53:12,000 --> 01:53:14,503
I argued that television
was a volatile industry...

1636
01:53:14,586 --> 01:53:18,423
in which success and failure
were determined week by week.

1637
01:53:19,466 --> 01:53:22,344
Mr. Jensen said he did not like
volatile industries...

1638
01:53:22,427 --> 01:53:26,140
and suggested with a certain
sinister silkiness...

1639
01:53:27,641 --> 01:53:31,228
that volatility in business
usually reflected bad management.

1640
01:53:32,521 --> 01:53:35,482
He didn't really care if Howard Beale
was the number one show or the 50th.

1641
01:53:35,566 --> 01:53:38,068
He didn't really care
if the Beale show lost money.

1642
01:53:39,194 --> 01:53:41,780
He wants Howard Beale on the air...

1643
01:53:41,864 --> 01:53:44,116
and he wants him kept on.

1644
01:53:44,158 --> 01:53:48,287
I would describe his position on this
as inflexible.

1645
01:53:50,205 --> 01:53:52,166
Where does that put us, Diana?

1646
01:53:53,292 --> 01:53:56,837
That puts us in the shithouse.
That's where that puts us.

1647
01:53:59,631 --> 01:54:02,509
Do you want me to go through this?

1648
01:54:03,635 --> 01:54:07,431
The Beale show Q score
is down to 33.

1649
01:54:08,515 --> 01:54:12,060
Most of this loss occurred in the child
and teen and 18-34 categories...

1650
01:54:12,144 --> 01:54:14,980
which were our key core markets.

1651
01:54:16,148 --> 01:54:18,817
It's the AR department's carefully
considered judgment, and mine...

1652
01:54:18,859 --> 01:54:23,489
that if we get rid of Beale, we should
maintain a respectable share...

1653
01:54:23,572 --> 01:54:25,782
with a comparable Q level.

1654
01:54:25,866 --> 01:54:29,328
The other show segments, Sybil the
Soothsayer, Jim Webbing, Vox Populi...

1655
01:54:29,411 --> 01:54:32,498
have all developed
their own audiences.

1656
01:54:32,539 --> 01:54:37,127
Our AR reports show that it is Beale
that is the destructive force here.

1657
01:54:38,337 --> 01:54:40,714
Minimally, we're talking about...

1658
01:54:40,756 --> 01:54:43,759
a ten-point differential in shares.

1659
01:54:43,842 --> 01:54:45,803
I think Joe oughta spell it out
for us.

1660
01:54:47,805 --> 01:54:50,891
A 28 share
is 80,000 dollar minutes.

1661
01:54:50,974 --> 01:54:53,685
I think we can sell complete positions
on the whole.

1662
01:54:53,727 --> 01:54:56,438
As a matter of fact, we're just getting
into the pre-Christmas gift-sellers...

1663
01:54:56,522 --> 01:55:00,108
and the agencies are coming back to me
with four-dollar CPMs.

1664
01:55:00,192 --> 01:55:05,197
If that's any indication, we're talking
$40-$45 million loss in annual revenues.

1665
01:55:05,280 --> 01:55:08,534
- Want the flak from the affiliates?
- We know all about it, Herb.

1666
01:55:08,575 --> 01:55:12,329
You would describe Mr. Jensen's position
on Beale as inflexible?

1667
01:55:12,412 --> 01:55:15,290
Intractable and adamantine.

1668
01:55:17,167 --> 01:55:20,379
What do we do about this Beale
son of a bitch?

1669
01:55:22,548 --> 01:55:24,800
I suppose we'll have to kill him.

1670
01:55:27,678 --> 01:55:30,639
I don't suppose you have any ideas
on that, Diana?

1671
01:55:34,101 --> 01:55:35,561
Well...

1672
01:55:37,437 --> 01:55:40,107
what would you fellas say
to an assassination?

1673
01:55:42,025 --> 01:55:44,570
I think I can get
the Mao Tse-tung people...

1674
01:55:44,653 --> 01:55:47,239
to kill Beale for us
as one of their shows.

1675
01:55:48,365 --> 01:55:53,036
In fact, it'll make a hell of
a kick-off show for the season.

1676
01:55:53,120 --> 01:55:56,039
We're facing heavy opposition on the
other networks for Wednesday nights...

1677
01:55:56,123 --> 01:55:59,585
and the "Mao Tse-tung Hour"
could use a sensational opener.

1678
01:56:01,795 --> 01:56:05,424
It could be done right on camera
in the studio.

1679
01:56:07,092 --> 01:56:09,303
We oughta get a fantastic
look-in audience...

1680
01:56:09,386 --> 01:56:12,514
for the assassination of Howard Beale
as our opening show.

1681
01:56:13,599 --> 01:56:16,310
If Beale dies...

1682
01:56:16,351 --> 01:56:20,439
what would our continuing obligation
to the Beale Corporation be?

1683
01:56:20,522 --> 01:56:23,609
I know our contract with Beale
contains a buy-out clause...

1684
01:56:23,650 --> 01:56:25,861
triggered by his death
or incapacity.

1685
01:56:25,944 --> 01:56:29,364
There must be a formula for
the computation of the purchase price.

1686
01:56:29,448 --> 01:56:33,452
Offhand, I think it was based on
a multiple of 1975 earnings...

1687
01:56:33,494 --> 01:56:37,331
with a base period in 1975,
which I think was 50 percent...

1688
01:56:37,372 --> 01:56:40,209
of salary, plus 25 percent
of the first year's profit...

1689
01:56:40,292 --> 01:56:43,420
multiplied by the unexpired portion
of the contract.

1690
01:56:43,504 --> 01:56:45,380
I don't think the show...

1691
01:56:45,464 --> 01:56:48,008
has any substantial syndication value,
would you say, Diana?

1692
01:56:48,091 --> 01:56:50,052
Syndication profits are minimal.

1693
01:56:51,220 --> 01:56:54,014
We're talking about a capital crime.

1694
01:56:55,057 --> 01:56:57,851
The network can't be implicated.

1695
01:57:08,195 --> 01:57:12,407
I hope you don't have any hidden
tape machines in this office, Frank.

1696
01:57:14,535 --> 01:57:17,496
The issue is,
shall we kill Howard Beale or not?

1697
01:57:17,579 --> 01:57:20,165
I'd like to hear
some more opinions on that.

1698
01:57:20,249 --> 01:57:23,710
I don't see we have any option.
Let's kill the son of a bitch.

1699
01:57:23,794 --> 01:57:25,462
Ladies and gentlemen,
let's hear it!

1700
01:57:25,546 --> 01:57:27,256
How do you feel?

1701
01:57:27,339 --> 01:57:29,007
We're mad as hell...

1702
01:57:29,049 --> 01:57:31,802
and we're not gonna
take this anymore!

1703
01:57:31,885 --> 01:57:35,639
Ladies and gentlemen, the "Network
News Hour" with Sybil the Soothsayer...

1704
01:57:39,226 --> 01:57:43,564
Jim Webbing and his
It's-the-Emmes-Truth Department.

1705
01:57:45,899 --> 01:57:49,987
Miss Mata Hari
and her skeletons in the closet.

1706
01:57:52,406 --> 01:57:54,700
Tonight another segment
of "Vox Populi."

1707
01:57:59,496 --> 01:58:03,876
And starring the Mad Prophet
of the Airways, Howard Beale!

1708
01:58:23,437 --> 01:58:27,858
...network news anchorman
on the UBS "Network News Show"...

1709
01:58:27,941 --> 01:58:31,904
known to millions
as the Mad Profit of the Airwaves...

1710
01:58:31,945 --> 01:58:35,741
was shot to death tonight in
a fusillade of automatic rifle fire...

1711
01:58:35,782 --> 01:58:38,035
just as he began
this evening's broadcast.

1712
01:58:38,118 --> 01:58:41,580
We never compromise,
so why should you?

1713
01:58:41,622 --> 01:58:45,042
Canada Dry Mixers.
Why compromise?

1714
01:58:45,125 --> 01:58:48,754
Have you seen the other side
of where you live?

1715
01:58:48,796 --> 01:58:52,633
- What's this stuff?
- Some cereal. It's good for you.

1716
01:58:52,716 --> 01:58:55,636
- Did you try it?
- I'm not gonna try it. You try it.

1717
01:58:55,677 --> 01:58:58,138
I'm not gonna try it.

1718
01:58:58,222 --> 01:59:00,224
- Let's get Mikey to try it!
- Yeah!

1719
01:59:00,307 --> 01:59:02,267
He won't eat it.
He hates everything.

1720
01:59:02,309 --> 01:59:06,271
The extraordinary incident occurred in
full view of his millions of viewers.

1721
01:59:06,355 --> 01:59:10,818
The assassins were members of
the Ecumenical Liberation Army...

1722
01:59:10,859 --> 01:59:12,986
two of whom were apprehended.

1723
01:59:13,070 --> 01:59:16,949
The leader of the group known
as the Great Ahmed Khan escaped.

1724
01:59:16,990 --> 01:59:19,493
This was the story of Howard Beale...

1725
01:59:19,535 --> 01:59:23,831
the first known instance of a man who
was killed because he had lousy ratings.


